      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sweat the vegetables",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Warm {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in a large saucepan over a medium heat. Add the onion, carrot, and celery. Season with salt and cook for 10 minutes until softened.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Add {{garlic}} of sliced garlic and cook for 2 minutes more.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add lentils and stock",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Add {{puy-lentils}} of rinsed Puy lentils, {{thyme}} of thyme, and {{bay-leaves}} of bay. Pour in {{stock-vegetable}} of hot vegetable stock.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Bring to a boil, then reduce to a steady simmer. Cook uncovered for 25 to 30 minutes until the lentils are completely tender.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Part-blend and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Remove the thyme sprigs and bay leaves. Use a stick blender to blend for 20 to 30 seconds only: this thickens the soup without destroying all the lentils.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Stir in {{red-wine-vinegar}} of red wine vinegar. Taste and adjust the seasoning. Serve with chopped flat-leaf parsley.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add more hot water and continue simmering. Do not add the vinegar until the lentils are fully cooked; acid prevents softening.",
              "cause": "Old lentils take longer to cook, as do lentils simmered in a very acidic stock.",
              "symptom": "Lentils are still firm after 30 minutes"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Stir in hot water or stock and adjust seasoning.",
              "cause": "Too much blending, or stock reduced heavily.",
              "symptom": "Soup is too thick"
            },
            {
              "fix": "A splash more red wine vinegar lifts the soup immediately. Taste after adding it.",
              "cause": "Acid was not added, or lentils absorbed all the flavour from the aromatics.",
              "symptom": "Tastes flat despite good seasoning"
            },
            {
              "fix": "No fix needed if the flavour is good. For colour, stir in a small handful of spinach before blending.",
              "cause": "Puy lentils do turn brownish when cooked; this is normal. Adding spinach or some fresh parsley blended in brightens the colour.",
              "symptom": "Colour is grey-brown"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Potage de lentilles is a workhorse of French home cooking, especially in the Auvergne where Puy lentils grow. The lentils are earthy and peppery. Their firm texture holds up to long cooking. The French home version is rarely the smooth purée served in restaurants. Home cooks part-blend or leave the lentils whole, then add the vinegar finish that sets the French style apart from most other European lentil soups.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
